'''Vanessa Hollingshead''' is an [[United States|American]] actress and stand-up comedian who has performed on many comedy programs including ''[[Comedy Central Presents]]'', ''[[Jongleurs|Live At Jongleurs]]'', ''[[Just For Laughs]]'', and ''[[Jim Breuer|The Jim Breuer Show]]''. She has also acted in a number of films, including a small role in the 1999 film, ''[[Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai]]''.<ref name="IMDb.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0391127/|title=Vanessa Hollingshead Filmography at IMDb.com|date=2009-03-28|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2009-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{ cite web | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0165798/awards | year=2001 | publisher = Internet Movie Database | accessdate = 2009-03-28 | title = Awards for Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai }}</ref>
==Early life== Hollingshead was born in [[New York City]]. Her father is [[Michael Hollingshead]], a British-born researcher who performed some of the first experiments with [[psychedelic drugs]] and [[hallucinogens]], and who introduced [[Timothy Leary]] and [[Paul McCartney]] to [[LSD]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://events.nbcnewyork.com/new-york-ny/events/show/86355483-vanessa-hollingshead-john-fugelsang|title=Vanessa Hollingshead Biography at NBC|date=2009-03-25|publisher=NBC|accessdate=2009-03-28}}</ref>
==Career== After years working as an [[temporary work|office temp]], in 1994 Hollingshead performed in an [[open mic]] night at the end of a four-hour-long night, claiming at the time "Even [[Richard Pryor]] wouldn't be funny at this point".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vocationvacations.com/DreamJobHolidays/vanessa-hollingshead.php|title=Test the dream job with comedian Vanessa Hollingshead in New York City|year=2008|publisher=VocationVocation|accessdate=2009-03-28}}</ref> Nine months later Hollingshead performed a twelve-minute slot at [[The Comic Strip Live]] on [[Second Avenue (Manhattan)|Second Avenue]], [[New York City]]. As a result of this performance she was offered a number of development deals and an offer to appear on ''[[The Drew Carey Show]]'', which she turned down. In 1996 she appeared on the ''Tompkins Square'' show hosted by [[Jeffrey Ross]] in her first [[television]] appearance. Further television appearances followed in 1997 and 1998, on ''[[Jongleurs|Live At Jongleurs]]'' and ''[[Jim Breuer|The Jim Breuer Show]]''. Whilst continuing with both live stand-up and television appearances (most notably when writing and appearing in ''[[Comedy Central|Comedy Central Presents]]'' in 2004), Hollingshead also appeared in several films. As well as appearing in [[Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai]], she appeared with [[ventriloquist]] act [[Otto & George]] and [[Jim Breuer]] again in the 2002 film ''American Dummy'', and opposite [[Greg Fitzsimmons]] and [[Pete Correale]] in the 2003 film ''The Gynecologists''.<ref name="IMDb.com"/> Hollingshead also runs comedy workshops for aspiring comedians.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/northamerica/usa/newyork/740976/Stand-up-for-the-virgin-comic.html|title=Stand Up For The Virgin Comic|date=2007-04-27|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=2009-03-28 | location=London | first=Kieran | last=Falconer}}</ref>
==Personal life== Hollingshead was married to Lucien Hold, the founder and manager of The Comic Strip Live in New York, whom she had first met when she appeared there in 1995. Hold died in 2004 from complications arising from [[scleroderma]]. This led to Hollingshead becoming an active member of The Scleroderma Foundation, an organization which campaigns for [[stem-cell research]] to find a cure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scleroderma.org/news/news2007/news2007_comedy-event2.shtm|title=Roster Set For Scleroderma Foundation Comedy Benefit|date=2007-05-09|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=2009-03-28 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121092935/http://www.scleroderma.org/news/news2007/news2007_comedy-event2.shtm |archivedate=2007-11-21}}</ref>
